message:
I agree that the timeouts - and `TimeoutException` - are confusing. Timeouts may or may not be a kind of cancellation. In the case where timeouts *are* a kind of cancellation, then they do throw `OperationCanceledException`.

I do cover a pattern that can be used for distinguishing timeouts from other cancellation in [the next post in this series](https://blog.stephencleary.com/2022/03/cancellation-3-detecting-cancellation.html). It would essentially look like this:

```C#
async Task DoSomethingAsync()
{
    using CancellationTokenSource cts = new(TimeSpan.FromMinutes(5));

    try
    {
        await DoThingAsync(cts.Token);
    }
    catch (OperationCanceledException ex) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
    {
        .. // Timeout has expired
    }
}
```

_"For example, you might choose to keep the start button enabled and just have it implicitly cancel the previous operation (if any)."_ 

In case we opted for this approach (not even having a cancel button), would you please shed some light on the best practice to cancel the previous operation (if any)? Thanks! 

I'm not sure if the following would be a bad practice. If we used "using", by the next time the start button was pressed (if the previous operation was still running), _cts would be invalid (disposed).

    async void StartButton_Click(..)
    {
        _cts?.Cancel();
        _cts?.Dispose();
        _cts = new();

        try
        {
            await DoSomethingAsync(_cts.Token);
            // ...
        }
        catch (Exception ex)
        {
            // ...
        }
    }

In case someone is reading this, and Stephen Clearly hasn't answered yet, I've come to this (better) approach:

    CancellationTokenSource? _cts = null;

    async void StartButton_Click(/*...*/)
    {
        // _cts is null when no DoSomethingAsync is running
        _cts?.Cancel();
        using CancellationTokenSource cts = _cts = new();

        try
        {
            await DoSomethingAsync(cts.Token);
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            // Operation canceled
        }
        finally
        {
            _if (cts == _cts)
            {
                _cts = null;
            }
        }
    }

"This cleanup is done when the CancellationTokenSource is cancelled or when it’s disposed."
Cancel does not dispose of resources after creating a linked source.
```
CancellationTokenSource top = new();

for (int i = 0; i < 1000; i++)
{
    CancellationTokenSource l = CancellationTokenSource.CreateLinkedTokenSource(top.Token);
    ////l.Dispose(); // cleans up memory
    l.Cancel(); // creates memory leak
}
```
